   "source": [
    "# Quick start guide\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7d207f40",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Overview\n",
    "\n",
    "Our goal with this quick start guide is to enable users to get good results on IBM Quantum systems with minimal effort and know-how.  In short, below outlines a good initial recipe for:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Transpiling circuits\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Applying basic error suppression techniques\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Optionally, performing readout error mitigation\n",
    "\n",
    "By design this guide does not go into the why and how of each step, but rather just presents the recipes in such a manner that an interested user can copy and paste the code into their projects."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "0685eeae",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:36.393524Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:35.213836Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

    "from qiskit import *\n",

    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "plt.style.use('ibmq-dark')\n",
    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina'"
   ]
  },

    "## Frontmatter\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Here will will show the best current compiling strategy for generic circuits.  As a concrete example we will take a Bernstein-Vazarani circuit and map it onto a 27Q system.  We begin by grabbing the target backend:"
   ]

   "source": [
    "## Best transpiling strategy"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e75ac6a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As a general rule it is always best to use `optimization_level=3` in Qiskit.  This uses the best swap mapping algorithm, and includes additional gate optimizations that can further optimize your circuits.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "172f0628",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n",
    "Explicitly turning off approximate gate synthesis is no longer necessary from qiskit 0.39+ or qiskit-terra 0.22+. The default setting is <font style=\"font-family:'Courier New'\">approximation_degree=1</font>, which now turns off gate approximation.</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "835346fb",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:57.989848Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:51.970471Z"
    },
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2208.79x2374.56 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1943,
       "width": 1809
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "trans_qc = transpile(qc, backend, optimization_level=3)\n",
    "trans_qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "98d90039",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-info\">In the latest version of Qiskit, and for <font style=\"font-family:'Courier New'\"> optimization_level>=2</font>, Qiskit automatically searches for a perfect qubit layout, i.e. one that satisfies all 2-qubit interactions, even without passing an <font style=\"font-family:'Courier New'\"> initial_layout</font> to the transpiler. If a perfect layout is not found, qubits are selected depending on calibration parameters of the backend whenever available. So it is no longer mandatory to use additional libraries such as <font style=\"font-family:'Courier New'\">mapomatic</font> in order to find a good layout of qubits to work with.</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "08260918",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Multiple Transpilation (optional)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "eb75caf5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The transpiler nominally has to add swap gates to map the circuit to the desired quantum hardware. The methods by which the swaps are added are stochastic, leading to a variable number of cnot gates in the output circuit. Because cnot gates are expensive in terms of error rates and duration, we want the circuit with the fewest cnot gates possible. Since ``qiskit-terra>=0.21.0``, Qiskit performs several trials of finding the best layout and swap mapping by itself. Transpiling multiple times (~10 or more) and taking the one with the lowest cnot gate count can still be a useful optimization.  For a single circuit this can be done as follows:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "0e020142",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:59.112892Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:57.991485Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of cnots: [14 21 19 11 17 17 12 14 17 12]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Transpile the circuit 'qc' 10 times\n",
    "trans_circ_list = transpile([qc]*10, backend, optimization_level=3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# get the number of cnot gates\n",
    "cx_counts = np.asarray([circ.count_ops().get('cx', 0) for circ in trans_circ_list])\n",
    "print('Number of cnots:', cx_counts)\n",
    "\n",
    "# select the circuit with the lowest number\n",
    "best_idx = np.argmin(cx_counts)\n",
    "best_trans_qc = trans_circ_list[best_idx]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "8248c6e9",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:01.170017Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:59.115102Z"
    },
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2197.85x618.722 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 521,
       "width": 1800
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "best_trans_qc.draw('mpl',idle_wires=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "78d3ab54",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Simple error suppression (optional)\n",
    "\n",
    "We can now apply dynamical decoupling (DD) to suppress some forms of errors.  Doing this requires a few additional imports.  Here we do a very simple DD gate (pulse) sequence of two X-gates."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "8207fdef",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.305127Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.302019Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from qiskit.circuit.library import XGate\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler import PassManager, InstructionDurations\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler.passes import ALAPScheduleAnalysis, PadDynamicalDecoupling"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f3324ff7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Because DD requires timing knowledge, we must get the duration of each operation that the backend supports."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "285cea52",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.313081Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.307492Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "durations = InstructionDurations.from_backend(backend)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "96ac4d72",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We also need to get the timing constraints that tell us the limitations of the device:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "e86087a6",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.319114Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.315729Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "constraints = backend.configuration().timing_constraints"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f0d96062",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally we have to get the timing information into the circuit and the DD gate sequences inserted into the idle times of the circuit:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "30d2f546",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:05.055806Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.321387Z"
    },
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2228.98x4799.28 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 10,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 3907,
       "width": 1825
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dd_sequence = [XGate(), XGate()]\n",
    "pm = PassManager([ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations),\n",
    "                  PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations, dd_sequence, \n",
    "                  pulse_alignment=constraints['pulse_alignment'])])\n",
    "opt_qc = pm.run(best_trans_qc)\n",
    "opt_qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "726f27af",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Readout error mitigation (optional)\n",
    "\n",
    "The basic circuit operations with the largest error rates on the IBM Quantum systems are measurements.  Given that microwave photons are some 5 orders of magnitude less energetic than their visible counterparts, this should not be surprising.  Luckily it is straightforward to reduce the impact of these errors through mitigation.  Here we will do so via M3."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "81d393fd",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-07T22:40:09.105405Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-07T22:40:09.088388Z"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n",
    "If you do not have M3 installed, you can do so via:<font style=\"font-family:'Courier New'\"> pip install mthree</font>.\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "2deb63de",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:05.087078Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:05.057511Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import mthree"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e772c0e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The first thing that needs to be done is to determine which physical qubits in the device are being measured in the circuit.  This can be done using the `final_measurement_mapping` function that returns a dictionary of `physical qubit : classical bit` key-value pairs:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "id": "95a8e964",

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4a1553a7",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-07T23:01:54.345732Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-07T23:01:54.340891Z"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "The above output may contain small negative values, indicating it is not a true probability distribution, bur rather is a **quasi-probability distribution**.  This is ok for computing expectation values that are at the heart of most near-term applications and algorithms.  For example, our above example ideally has an expectation value $\\langle ZZZZZ\\rangle=-1$.  The raw results yield:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "143fb30e",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:39:05.632937Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:39:05.627890Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "-0.4722"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mthree.utils.expval(raw_counts, 'ZZZZZ')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "38f89547",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "394c7b91",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So we see that indeed, the readout error mitigation gives an improved expectation value.  It is important to note that this does come with an increase in the corresponding standard deviation, and thus one needs to execute more circuits to obtain a desired precision.\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, if one wants a true probability distribution then it is possible to compute the closest one to the quasi-distribution"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "59c1138c",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {

     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:39:05.642836Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "probs = quasi.nearest_probability_distribution()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "76851938",
   "metadata": {},

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "id": "722c4f76",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:39:05.659099Z",

    }
   },
   "outputs": [
